Chapter 3: The Guild of the Chosen

Chapter 3: The Guild of the Chosen

The air in the Low District tasted of wet stone and boiled cabbage. Kael leaned against a doorway that had once been grand, now slumping like a drunkard’s shoulder, and watched the rain turn the cobbles to a river of filthy mirrors. In his hand was a token—a chit of black iron stamped with a gilded sun. It felt heavier than a crown.

Elara was gone, vanished into the warren of scribes and forgotten archives she called a ‘network.’ The hidden temple she’d spoken of was a ghost story. This, she’d insisted, pressing the token into his palm, was the next best thing. “To know the monster, walk into its mouth,” she’d said, her scholar’s eyes alight with a fervor that bordered on madness. “Your mercenary friend, Bor, can get you inside. See what they are. Then we’ll know.”

Bor. A mountain of scarred muscle and pragmatic cruelty, who’d shared a dozen battlefields and one memorable brothel fire with Kael. He now ran ‘security acquisitions’ for the Guild of the Chosen. Hired muscle for the muscle-makers, Kael thought, his smile a thin, bitter line.

He found Bor in a steam-filled bathhouse, his bulk submerged like a sleeping leviathan. The man’s eyes, small and shrewd, opened as Kael approached.

“Kael. Heard you stirred up some shit at the Auction. Got a price on your head from House Vel’Thorn.” Bor’s voice was a gravelly rumble. “Not smart.”

“I need work,” Kael said, tossing the token. It landed with a soft plink in the water near Bor’s chest.

Bor fished it out, squinted. “Guild work. You? You’ve got a mouth like a rusty hinge and the respect for authority of a feral cat.”

“I can stand still and look threatening. It’s my best skill.”

Bor chuckled, a sound like stones grinding. “They’re hiring for the inner sanctum. Guarding the ‘sacred relics.’” He made a crude gesture that left little doubt about what he thought of the relics. “Pay is stupid good. But you see anything, you forget it. You hear anything, it dies in your skull. They’re not just pompous asses in there, Kael. They’re the kind of rich that buys consequences and sells the leftovers.”

“Just need the coin,” Kael lied.

Bor studied him for a long moment, then nodded. “Be at the Postern Gate at dawn. Wear something without visible bloodstains. And for pity’s sake, try to look impressed.”
The Guildhall wasn’t a building; it was a geological event. White marble, quarried from mountains a thousand leagues away, soared into the capital’s perpetual gloom, defying it. Gilded spires pierced the low clouds, and the great seal of the Chosen—a stylized sun cradling a sword—was etched into every surface, so omnipresent it became invisible. Kael, amidst a line of twenty other grim-faced sellswords, was processed through gates that thudded shut with the finality of a tomb seal.

Inside, the air changed. It was warm, scentless, and dry, carrying a faint, antiseptic hum. The sounds of the city vanished, replaced by the soft shuffle of felt-slippered feet and the distant, melodic drone of a choir practicing hymns to the Prophecy. The light came from great crystalline globes set in the ceiling, casting a shadowless, even glow. It felt less like a holy order and more like a very clean, very expensive prison.

Their assignment was the Hall of Annals, a vast, circular library that spiraled down into the bedrock. Their sergeant, a Guild-man named Evin with the polished demeanor of a head waiter and the eyes of a pit viper, laid out the rules.

“You are scenery,” Evin said, his hands clasped behind his back. “You do not speak to the acolytes, the scribes, or the Chosen. You do not read the scrolls. You do not think profound thoughts. You stand. You occasionally patrol the prescribed route. You are a moving part of the architecture. Deviation will be treated as heresy.”

For the first two days, Kael was the perfect part. He stood at his archway, watching the silent ballet of the Guild. Young men and women in cream-and-gold robes moved with serene purpose. Older, more ornate figures—Prophets, they were called—held quiet conferences in alcoves. It was orderly, peaceful, and utterly soulless.

On the third day, he saw the training.

He was on a patrol route that passed a gallery overlooking a sunken courtyard. Below, a boy of no more than sixteen, wearing the gilded sash of the current Chosen, was practicing. But not with a swordmaster. A man in a Prophet’s robe stood beside him, speaking softly. Before the boy was a peasant actor, shaking in rags.

“The Shadow of Despair grips him, son of the Sun,” the Prophet intoned, his voice carrying. “His heart is a nest of serpents. Only the Light of your Truth can cleanse him.”

The boy, his face a mask of earnest concentration, placed a hand on the actor’s head. “Be cleansed,” he recited. The actor fell to his knees, weeping fabricated tears of gratitude. A scribe nearby took meticulous notes.

In another corner of the yard, a past Chosen—a man in his thirties, his eyes hollow—was being coached through a speech for a provincial festival. “Louder on ‘destiny,’” a voice-director snapped. “We need to feel the quiver in the upper balcony.”

Kael watched, a cold stone settling in his gut. This was the forge of heroes. A theater. A scripted sham. The gritty, morally complex truth he lived every day was sanded down here into a smooth, marketable peg for the round hole of prophecy.

His break came during the night watch. The sanctum was empty, the crystal lights dimmed to a ghostly blue. Evin, believing his scenery to be mindless, had left a ledger on a lectern. It was a mundane thing: supply requisitions. But Kael’s eyes, trained to spot value and weakness, skimmed the entries. Not for food, or parchment, or ink. For alchemical reagents. Nightshade extract. Phantasmic spores. Forged demonic sigils (mass-produced, noted with a quantity discount). And payments: to the “Grey Traders of the Whispering Pass,” to the “Mercenary Company of the Shattered Banner,” to “House Vel’Thorn for logistical support.”

His mind connected the dots with a series of sickening clicks. The “Shadow of Despair” the boy-Chosen had “cleansed” was a peasant actor. But the Shadow that terrorized a province, the one that required the noble houses to buy “Guild-blessed protections” and the peasantry to tithe two-thirds of their grain for “prophetic wards”… where did that come from? The ledger suggested an answer: from the Guild’s own storerooms, via intermediaries.

They weren’t just managing the prophecy. They were manufacturing the demand.

A rage, quiet and deep, began to burn in Kael. It was the same rage he’d felt watching the Auction, but now it had a source, a ledger line. It was the rage of a man who’d fought real monsters in the dark, only to find the true monsters owned the light and sold tickets to the fight.

He began to use his patrols differently. He memorized guard rotations, noted which doors were merely locked and which were warded with faintly glowing sigils. He found the Archives of Outcomes—a euphemistic title for a records hall of past Chosen campaigns.

One night, when the hum of the place was at its lowest, he picked a lock (a simple, arrogant lock—who would dare steal from the Guild?) and slipped inside.

The air was thick with dust and the smell of old vellum. He lit a shuttered lantern. Rows upon rows of scrolls, each tagged with a year and a Chosen’s name. He moved back through time, past records of staged victories and paid-off bandit kings. He reached the era of the Great Purge, the time when the old sigils were erased, the true heir vanished.

And there, he found it. Operation: Sundered Star. Authorization: High Prophetic Council. Objective: Neutralize the schismatic cult at the Monastery of the Unfallen Moon, which propagates the false sigil and heretical lineage. Contractor: The Shattered Banner Company.

Kael’s breath stopped. The words swam before his eyes. Monastery of the Unfallen Moon. It was not a name from a scholar’s tale. It was the place of his earliest, faintest memories. The smell of pine and incense. The sound of a deep bell. A woman’s voice, singing. A flash of a sigil—his sigil—carved into stone.

He’d been told he was found in the ashes. A refugee. An orphan of some vague conflict.

He was a survivor of a sanctioned extermination. The Guild had ordered his home destroyed. The Shattered Banner—Bor’s old company, the one he’d bragged about for years—had carried it out.

The cold rage in him turned volcanic, molten. He gripped the edge of the shelf until the wood groaned. The mark on his chest seemed to burn, a brand of ice and fire.

Blindly, he stumbled to another section, a gallery of portraits. Past Chosen, Prophets, Benefactors. His eyes, scouring the faces of the killers, the accountants of genocide, landed on a small, dust-covered painting in a corner, away from the glorious light.

It was labeled simply: Linnae, of the Blood.

The woman was young, her hair dark, her bearing regal even in the stiff formal style. But it was the eyes that struck him like a physical blow. They were gray, storm-colored, sharp with a intelligence that the painter had captured despite himself. They were his eyes. The exact shape, the same unsettling mix of intensity and distance. She wore a simple pendant. A moon, cradling a single star.

The sigil. The true sigil.

The world narrowed to the face in the painting. The hum of the Guildhall faded. This was no abstract heir. This was a woman. This was… his mother. The word felt foreign and immense in his mind. He had come looking for corruption, for a system to hate. He had found a ledger entry for his own murder and the ghost of a mother in a forgotten frame.

“Beautiful, wasn’t she?”

The voice came from the doorway. Soft, cultured, utterly devoid of warmth.

Kael whirled, his dagger half-drawn before his mind even registered the threat.

Guild Master Thaddeus stood there, not in robes, but in a rich, dark velvet doublet. He was an older man, his hair silver, his face a map of gentle wrinkles that didn’t reach his pale blue eyes. He looked like a kind grandfather. He held no weapon. He didn’t need to. Two silent, hulking figures—true Guild enforcers, not hired muscle—flanked him, their presence sucking the air from the room.

“The last true spark,” Thaddeus continued, stepping into the lantern light, his gaze on the portrait. “Stubborn. Idealistic. A tragedy, really.” He finally looked at Kael, and his eyes flickered to the hand still clenched on the shelf. “You have her hands, too. And, I suspect, her unfortunate penchant for being where she does not belong.”

Kael said nothing. Every instinct screamed to fight, to lunge, but the calculus of the two brutes in the doorway was absolute. He was caught.

“You’ve had a busy night, Kael. Or should I use your birth name? Kaelen? It’s on the survivor list from Sundered Star. A footnote. ‘Child, male, presumed deceased.’ Presumptions are so often wrong.” Thaddeus sighed, a sound of genuine, weary disappointment. “We’ve been aware of Elara’s little cabal for months. We let her lead you here. It was… more efficient.”

The betrayal was so complete it was almost funny. Elara, the true believer, had been a fishing line, and he the dumb, raging trout. The hook in his mouth was his own history.

“Why?” Kael ground out, the first word he’d spoken feeling like broken glass in his throat.

“To meet you. To see what the bloodline produced in the wild. A mercenary. How… pragmatic.” Thaddeus gestured, and the two enforcers moved forward. Kael’s dagger was a useless toothpick against them. A pressure-point strike to his neck, and his world dissolved into numb, buzzing paralysis. They caught him before he fell, holding him upright like a broken doll.

He was not taken to a dungeon. He was carried, politely, to the Guild Master’s personal chambers—a room of breathtaking luxury, lined with books and rare artifacts. They deposited him in a deep, plush chair facing a cold fireplace. His body tingled, slowly returning to his control.

Thaddeus poured two glasses of amber liquor from a decanter. He handed one to Kael. Kael didn’t move to take it.

“Suit yourself.” Thaddeus sat opposite him, sipping. “You’ve seen our little operation. The training. The ledgers. You think us monsters.”

“You are,” Kael rasped.

“We are gardeners,” Thaddeus corrected gently. “The Prophecy is a wild, untamed vine. Left alone, it chokes everything—kingdoms, lives, the very notion of order. We prune it. We guide it. We make it bear fruit that feeds the world.”

“You sell the rot and call it fruit.”

“We sell stability!” Thaddeus said, his voice gaining an edge of passion. “Before the Guild, the true Prophecy threw up champions and villains on a whim. Entire cities were sacrificed for ‘narrative symmetry.’ It was chaos wearing a crown of stars. We brought reason. We created a system where the Chosen is manageable, the threats are containable, and the economy… thrives. Yes, we manufacture some threats. Far better a controllable demon than a real one. We provide a service, Kael. A necessary, profitable service.”

He leaned forward, his grandfatherly face earnest. “But the system is aging. The noble houses grow restless. The common people’s faith is a thin veneer. They need to believe again, deeply. A manufactured Chosen from a merchant’s son won’t do it anymore.”

Thaddeus’s pale eyes locked onto Kael’s. “But a true heir? The lost son of Linnae, returning from the wilderness, bearing the forgotten sigil, chosen by the very Guild that once opposed his line… now reconciled to the greater good?” He spread his hands, a beatific smile on his lips. “It’s the perfect story. It has legitimacy. It has poetry. It has truth at its core.”

The offer hung in the scented air, more grotesque than any torture.

“You want me,” Kael said, disbelief warring with revulsion, “to be your Chosen One.”

“We want you to be the Chosen One,” Thaddeus corrected. “The final one. The one who legitimizes our rule for the next thousand years. You will want for nothing. Power, wealth, adoration. You can even have your revenge, in a way—command the Shattered Banner Company yourself. Dissolve them. Execute Bor, if you like. A fine first act of justice for your new reign.”

He gestured to the portrait of Linnae, which one of the enforcers had quietly brought and placed on a side table. “Honor her memory by saving the world from the chaos she championed. Be the king in the gilded cage, instead of the corpse in the unmarked grave.”

Kael looked from the portrait—his mother’s storm-gray eyes pleading from a past he never knew—to the Guild Master’s serene, expectant face. The hook was baited with everything he’d just learned he’d lost. It was the most morally complex trap ever devised.

He thought of the boy in the courtyard, practicing his lines. He thought of the ledger entries for nightshade and fake sigils. He thought of Bor’s laughter in the steam, and the smell of his own past burning.

He finally reached out, took the glass of liquor, and drained it in one burning gulp. He met Thaddeus’s gaze.

“Let’s talk about my salary,” Kael said, his voice flat, his new eyes utterly unreadable.